The Operations department authorizes maintenance and other work in their area and issues permits for all hot work (e.g. grinding, burning, welding, and brazing) performed on or near covered processes. The hot work permit is terminated when conditions within the work environment become unsafe or hazardous, when conditions of its issuance change. 

Two copies of the hot work permit are maintained. The first is available at the physical location of the hot work for the duration of the job. The second is maintained in the Operations control room until work is completed or suspended. After hot work is complete, a copy of the permit is maintained on file in the Administrative Building for at least one year. 

The hot work permit and associated Job Safety Analysis (JSAs) contains the following information:
	The effective date and time;
	The place of use;
	The hours during which the source of ignition may be used, not to exceed 24 hours;
	The specific location or piece of equipment where the source of ignition will be used; 
	The nature of the use of the source of ignition; and,
	Any special precautions or limitations to be observed before, during, or after the use of the source of ignition, including the need for a fire watch and fire hoses or extinguishers. The criteria for needing a fire watch and the responsibilities of the fire watch are identified within the hot work permit.

Safety (including hot work) permits are issued at the job site. The issuer of the permit performs an inspection of the area to ensure the following prior to authorization of the hot work permit:
